STS 112: Lab 6

James Chapman

In this lab, we will make more population pyramids to explore the effects of immigration legislation on immigration to the United States from a variety of countries.

Getting started

Load tidyverse and read in the data for Week 6. Remove records for Alaska and Hawaii.

library(tidyverse)
ipums = read_csv("wk6_small.csv") %>% filter(YEAR > 1950 | !STATEFIP %in% c(2,15))
ipums %>% filter(YEAR < 1960 & STATEFIP %in% c(2,15))

Classifying birthplaces

In this lab, we will only be making pyramids for individuals born outside the United States, but we want to graph their numbers as a proportion of the total population. For that reason, we will keep individuals born in the United States in the data frame until the end. Create a new variable called BPLACE that classifies BPL and/or BPLD into the following categories: United States, Western Hemisphere, Northern and Western Europe, Southern and Eastern Europe, Asia, Other.

#Note: US OUTLYING AREA/TERRITORIES are being included in the United States Category.

birthplace = ipums %>% mutate(BPLACE = ifelse(BPL <= 120, 1,
                                       ifelse(BPL <= 300, 2,
                                       ifelse(BPL <= 440, 3,
                                       ifelse(BPL <= 499, 4,
                                       ifelse(BPL <= 599, 5, 6)))))) %>%
             mutate(BPLACE = factor(BPLACE, labels = c("United States", "W. Hemisphere", "N. & W. Europe", "S. & E. Europe", "Asia", "Other")))

Making population pyramids

Now add age groups and factor SEX.

agegrp <- "0-9"
for (n in (1:7)) {
  agegrp <- c(agegrp, paste(n, "0-", n, "9", sep = ""))
}
agegrp <- c(agegrp, "80+")

birthplace = birthplace %>% mutate(SEXF = factor(SEX, labels = c("Male", "Female"))) %>%
                            mutate(AGEG = factor(ifelse(AGE >= 80, 8, AGE %/% 10), labels = agegrp))

Create column n, representing the number of people in each unique combination of YEAR, BPLACE, SEXF, and AGEG (the numerator), and create column TOTAL, representing the total number of people in each year (the denominator).

birthplace = birthplace %>% group_by(YEAR) %>% 
                     count(BPLACE, SEXF, AGEG, wt = PERWT) %>% 
                     mutate(TOTAL = sum(n))

Change n values for men to negative values and remove rows for individuals born in the United States.

birthplace <- birthplace %>% filter(BPLACE != "United States") %>% mutate(n = ifelse(SEXF == "Male", 0-n, n))

Now plot the population pyramids, faceting on BPLACE and animating by YEAR. You will need to adjust the breaks and labels on the y-axis to make the pyramids legible. Pay attention to legibility of the breaks and labels on the y-axis.

pyramid = ggplot(birthplace, aes(AGEG, n/TOTAL, fill = SEXF)) + geom_col() + coord_flip() + scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Set1") + 
  scale_y_continuous(breaks = seq(-.01, .01, .005), 
                     labels = c("1%", ".5%","0%", ".5%","1%")) +
  theme_minimal(base_size = 40) + theme(legend.position = "bottom") +
  labs(x = "Age", y = "Percent of Population", fill = "Sex", title = "Population Pyramid") +
  facet_grid(cols = vars(BPLACE))
pyramid

library(gganimate)
library(gifski)

options(gganimate.dev_args = list(width = 1800, height = 860))
pyramid + transition_manual(YEAR) + labs(title = "Population Pyramid, {current_frame}")
anim_save("pyramid1.gif")
